Test Code
 
# TC-03: GUI Integration Test
# Tester  : Nitin Agrawal
# Purpose : Verify all 3 modules work together in GUI
# Run     : sudo python3 tests/test_gui.py
 
import tkinter as tk
from threading import Thread
from scapy.all import ARP, Ether, srp, sniff
 
def log(msg):
    output.insert(tk.END, msg + '\n')
    output.see(tk.END)
 
# ---- TEST SCAN ----
def test_scan():
    network = subnet_entry.get()
    log("[*] Testing Scan Module...")
    arp    = ARP(pdst=network)
    ether  = Ether(dst="ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:ff")
    result = srp(ether/arp, timeout=2, verbose=0)[0]
    if result:
        log("[+] Scan Working")
        for sent, received in result:
            log(f"{received.psrc} --> {received.hwsrc}")
    else:
        log("[-] Scan failed or no devices found")
 
# ---- TEST DETECTION ----
def test_detect():
    log("[*] Testing Detection Module...")
    def process(packet):
        if packet.haslayer(ARP) and packet.op == 2:
            log(f"[!] ARP Reply: {packet.psrc} is at {packet.hwsrc}")
    sniff(filter="arp", prn=process, store=0)
 
# ---- TEST SPOOF (SAFE MODE) ----
def test_spoof():
    target  = target_entry.get()
    gateway = gateway_entry.get()
    log("[*] Testing Spoof Module...")
    log(f"[+] Simulating: {target} <--> {gateway}")
    log("[+] Safe mode — no real packets sent")
    log("[+] Spoof Module Working")
 

How The Code Works — Step by Step
1.	test_scan() — Identical ARP broadcast scan logic as TC-01. Output goes to the GUI text console instead of terminal print(). Tests that scan works inside the GUI context.
2.	test_detect() — Calls sniff() in a background Thread so the GUI stays fully responsive while detection runs. Tests threading integration.
3.	test_spoof() — Safe simulation mode. Reads Target IP and Gateway IP from GUI entry fields, confirms the input logic and module wiring works — without sending real packets.
4.	All three tests share one Tkinter GUI window — validates that all modules integrate and co-exist without conflicts.

